te>=30 -> round up\ndef round_nearest_hour(dt):\n    if dt.minute >= 30 or (dt.minute==29 and dt.second>=30):\n        dt = dt.replace(minute=0, second=0, microsecond=0) + timedelta(hours=1)\n    else:\n        dt = dt.replace(minute=0, second=0, microsecond=0)\n    return dt\n\ndl['epoch_hr'] = dl['epoch'].apply(round_nearest_hour)\n# For each hour, take mean a\nhourly_a = dl.groupby('epoch_hr')['a_km'].mean().sort_index()\n# compute hourly delta a (change per hour): we'll compute difference between consecutive hours\nhourly_df = hourly_a.reset_index().rename(columns={'epoch_hr':'time','a_km':'a'})\nhourly_df['delta_a'] = hourly_df['a'].diff()\n# Keep May 1-30 range\nstart = datetime(2024,5,1)\nend = datetime(2024,5,30,23,59,59)\nhourly_df = hourly_df[(hourly_df['time']>=start) & (hourly_df['time']<=end)].reset_index(drop=True)\n\nprint('TLE hourly rows:', len(hourly_df))\nprint(hourly_df.head())\n\n# parse OMNI2 fixed-width columns: spec in omni2.text but inspect first few lines to infer AP column index\nomni_lines = open(omni_path).read().splitlines()\nprint('\\nOMNI sample lines:', len(omni_lines))\nfor ln in omni_lines[:5]:\n    print(ln)\n\n# OMNI2 format: columns are year, month, day, hour, ... AP is one of the columns. From preview earlier, the sequence: year, month, day, ... values; need to find 'ap' column index. Search header spec file omni2.text in dataset\n# Let's grep for 'omni2.text' file in dataset listing\n\n# Instead, deduce AP column by known OMNI2 order: According to OMNI2 daily/hourly data, AP index appears as column 9? But better: find column count and try to find typical AP value ranges (0-400?) AP often small e.g. 5.3, 5.4 in sample. In preview lines after date fields we saw numbers 5.3 5.1 -7.3 ... So AP maybe first value after hour? The preview shows: '2024   1  0 2596 51 52  60  36   5.3   5.1  -7.3 ...' Likely ap = 5.3 (planetary A index?) and ap_3hr = 5.1? We'll assume column 8 (0-based index 8?)\n\n# Let's parse by splitting whitespace 